                                <condition>The inscription is damaged in places and partially inaccessible.</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout style="vertical" rend="arris_up">The inscription reads upwards on the left angle, continuing across the top and down the other angle. According to Brash (1879, 268) it commences <q>1 ft. 2in. from the bottom [0.35m]...finishing within 1ft. 5in. [0.43m] of the bottom</q>.</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The inscription is quite broadly and deeply <rs type="execution"  key="pocked" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/11.html">pocked</rs>. <height></height>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <origPlace><placeName type="townland">Windgap (<distinct xml:lang="ga"><ref target="https://www.logainm.ie/en/49060">Bearna na Gaoithe</ref></distinct>)</placeName> <placeName type="county">Co. Waterford</placeName> <placeName type="country">Ireland</placeName>
                                <geo>52.34163, -7.49245</geo>
                            <note>ITM Coordinates: 634584, 621224</note>
                            </origPlace>
                            <origDate/><!--usually not known-->
                        </origin>
                        <provenance type="found" when="1851">Found associated with a souterrain (WA003-007005-), possibly a displaced lintel, in a rath (WA003-007001-) in 1851 by Du Noyer (1857, 251). One of possibly two from this site. Macalister (1945, 296, no. 308) notes that a statement in Hitchcock's notebook records the fact that he had heard from Windele of a second inscribed stone at this place; but that when he went in search of it he learned that it had been turned into a roller for agricultural purposes, and that the inscription had thus been destroyed. 
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance type="observed">In the north-west quadrant of the interior of the rath. Examined and photographed in September 2025 as part of the OG(H)AM project.
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
